1 terminated based upon the debtor's assertion that a particular debt, or portion
2 thereof, being collected is coerced debt.
3 "§ 1H-6. Order establishing relief from coerced debt.
4 (a) A debtor may bring an action against a claimant to establish that a particular debt, or
5 portion thereof, is coerced debt.
6 (b) In an action brought by a claimant to recover a particular debt against the debtor, the
7 debtor may file a cross-complaint to establish that the particular debt, or portion thereof, is
8 coerced debt. The notice described in G.S. 1H-5(c) shall not be required as a prerequisite to filing
9 a cross-complaint. A debtor shall plead the allegations of coerced debt with particularity and shall
10 do either of the following:
11 (1) Attach the documents provided to the claimant pursuant to G.S. 1H-5(a) to
12 any complaint.
13 (2) Attach the documents identified in G.S. 1H-5(a) to any cross-complaint.
14 (c) If the debtor establishes by a preponderance of the evidence that the particular debt,
15 or portion thereof, is coerced debt, the debtor shall be entitled to the following relief:
16 (1) A declaratory judgment that the debtor is not obligated to the claimant on the
17 particular debt, or portion thereof, that is coerced debt.
18 (2) An injunction prohibiting the claimant from holding or attempting to hold the
19 debtor personally liable on the particular debt, or portion thereof, that is
20 coerced debt, and prohibiting the claimant from enforcing a judgment related
21 to the particular debt, or portion thereof, that is coerced debt against the debtor.
22 (3) An order dismissing any cause of action brought by the claimant to enforce or
23 collect on the particular debt from the debtor or, if only a portion of the debt
24 is established as coerced debt, an order directing that the complaint and
25 judgment, if any, in the action be amended to reflect only the portion of the
26 particular debt that is not coerced debt.
27 (c1) If the debtor establishes by a preponderance of the evidence that the particular debt,
28 or portion thereof, is coerced debt, the court shall issue a judgment in favor of the claimant against
29 the person or persons who coerced the debtor into incurring the debt in the amount of the debt,
30 or portion thereof, that is coerced debt, provided that the person or persons who coerced the
31 debtor into incurring the debt or debts has been brought within the jurisdiction of the court and
32 joined as a party to the action and the evidence supports such a judgment. The court presiding
33 over the action shall take the appropriate steps necessary to prevent abuse of the debtor or an
34 immediate family member of the debtor, including, but not limited to, sealing court records,
35 redacting personally identifiable information about the debtor and any immediate family member
36 of the debtor, and directing that any deposition or evidentiary hearing be conducted remotely.
37 (d) A debtor who files knowingly false motions, pleadings, or other papers or engages in
38 other tactics that are frivolous or intended to cause unnecessary delay against a claimant shall be
39 liable for the claimant's attorneys' fees and costs in defending the lawsuit.
40 (e) The claimant may move the court to make written findings regarding evidence related
41 to the person who caused the coerced debt to be incurred.
42 "§ 1H-7. Miscellaneous provisions.
43 (a) Where some or all of a claim is established as having arisen from coerced debt, a
44 claimant shall have standing, and may use all rights and remedies, to collect by any lawful means
45 that claim, or portion thereof, from the person or persons determined to have coerced the debt,
46 or against a person who used or possessed money, goods, services, or property obtained through
47 coerced debt.
48 (b) The statute of limitations for a claimant to bring an action to collect coerced debt from
49 any person determined to have coerced the debt shall run from the date of the court's
50 determination that the person caused the duress, intimidation, threat of force, force, fraud, or
House Bill 515-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 undue influence giving rise to the coerced debt at issue and shall be brought within five years of
2 that determination.
3 (c) If any provision of this Chapter or the application thereof to any person or
4 circumstances is held invalid, such invalidity shall not affect other provisions or applications of
5 this Chapter that can be given effect without the invalid provision or application and, to this end,
6 the provisions of this Chapter are severable.
7 (d) This Chapter applies only to debts incurred on or after July 1, 2025, except that a
8 debtor may file a cross-complaint described by subsection (b) of this section in an action filed by
9 a claimant to collect a debt incurred prior to July 1, 2025, unless a final judgment has been entered
10 in that action."
11 SECTION 2. This act becomes effective July 1, 2025.
